1
00:00:02,544 --> 00:00:15,422
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

2
00:00:18,306 --> 00:00:22,731
So the question was, what was the Buddha's greatest discovery?

3
00:00:24,875 --> 00:00:26,477
So,

4
00:00:27,588 --> 00:00:42,908
There are lots of people who follow Buddha Dhamma, they get a lot from the practice and the teachings, who themselves are some form of materialists, atheists, scientific materialists and so on.

5
00:00:45,472 --> 00:00:50,460
You can understand how they get the benefit from it, because you don't have to believe anything.

6
00:00:51,100 --> 00:00:55,587
That's the great thing about the Buddha Dhamma, you have to explore it yourself.

7
00:00:56,460 --> 00:01:06,400
But it does baffle me that some people sort of deny the transcendence of Nibbana or of the Buddha's achievement.

8
00:01:08,164 --> 00:01:14,757
He himself referred to himself as the Tathagata, which translates rather badly as thus gone.

9
00:01:16,171 --> 00:01:22,120
But the best translation I've seen is the transcendent one, one who has transcended.

10
00:01:22,201 --> 00:01:23,263
What's he transcended?

11
00:01:23,644 --> 00:01:25,046
Well, he's transcended suffering.

12
00:01:25,087 --> 00:01:26,969
He's transcended samsara.

13
00:01:27,531 --> 00:01:29,694
But I think it goes much deeper than that.

14
00:01:31,597 --> 00:01:39,512
So, involved in that is also perhaps a wrong understanding about the teaching of not-self.

15
00:01:40,757 --> 00:01:49,587
in the discourse on the teaching of not-self, he simply asks, you know, if you look at your body, what can you control?

16
00:01:49,947 --> 00:01:51,368
You know, we think we are the body.

17
00:01:52,230 --> 00:01:55,754
We think we're our emotions, but we find ourselves ruled by everything.

18
00:01:55,933 --> 00:02:00,698
And there's very little thing, there's very little I can do about the lack of hair on my head.

19
00:02:01,881 --> 00:02:02,981
It's a bit late anyway.

20
00:02:03,462 --> 00:02:04,183
Never mind.

21
00:02:05,141 --> 00:02:30,930
and then there's all that business about impermanence and if something is impermanent then obviously it can't be substantial and so on and so forth right i'm sure you all know that so what i want to do is take his victory verse so that's the first thing we'll look at and this is what he says through many births i wandered in samsara the world of suffering

22
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:34,983
Seeking but not finding the builder of this house.

23
00:02:36,324 --> 00:02:38,346
Painful is repeated birth.

24
00:02:38,926 --> 00:02:41,489
So this house, of course, he's referring to himself.

25
00:02:41,549 --> 00:02:45,372
Yeah, the heart, the psychophysical organism.

26
00:02:46,492 --> 00:02:48,955
Oh, house builder, you are seen.

27
00:02:49,795 --> 00:02:51,818
You will not build this house for me again.

28
00:02:52,337 --> 00:02:54,180
All your rafters are broken.

29
00:02:54,620 --> 00:02:57,062
The ridge pole is shattered.

30
00:02:58,584 --> 00:03:01,086
My mind has attained the unconditioned.

31
00:03:01,993 --> 00:03:02,555
Chitta.

32
00:03:02,634 --> 00:03:03,616
He uses the word Chitta.

33
00:03:03,635 --> 00:03:04,377
We'll come back to that.

34
00:03:05,177 --> 00:03:07,542
And I have reached the end of craving.

35
00:03:08,462 --> 00:03:08,804
Okay.

36
00:03:10,445 --> 00:03:13,750
So here he's using a metaphor for the self, the house builder.

37
00:03:14,891 --> 00:03:19,699
And through the house builder, we build this world that we're living in.

38
00:03:19,899 --> 00:03:20,879
This is our house.

39
00:03:21,901 --> 00:03:27,729
When you think about it, you see, everything is happening within your body, within the mind.

40
00:03:29,111 --> 00:03:30,633
And then we project everything.

41
00:03:31,019 --> 00:03:31,920
onto the world.

42
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:34,084
I mean, it's sort of magical, really.

43
00:03:35,627 --> 00:03:40,194
So we're in this bubble of consciousness, our own little bubble of consciousness.

44
00:03:41,356 --> 00:03:44,823
And it's up to us to make it a fairly nice place to live in it.

45
00:03:46,986 --> 00:03:53,617
And we've made mistakes in the past, led by delusion, and made a hash of it to some extent or another.

46
00:03:57,530 --> 00:04:16,947
So what he's saying is that once he's found the cause of this house that's built, which is the self, right, this delusive idea of a self, then he was able to escape all the suffering that that delusion made for him.

47
00:04:17,428 --> 00:04:25,055
Now, this word citta, you see, the problem for the Buddha was that he had discovered something for which the language

48
00:04:25,492 --> 00:04:51,600
couldn't express and i'm not so sure any language can but he's stuck with words that have other meanings so he'll talk about the chitta chitta means the mind the heart mind it's the emotional and thought life what we might understand by the greek word psyche and but here it's obviously not that because

49
00:04:51,935 --> 00:04:57,019
the psyche as we know it, the body-heart-mind complex, is conditioned.

50
00:04:57,660 --> 00:05:02,285
But he says he's attained the unconditioned citta.

51
00:05:03,165 --> 00:05:11,333
So he's pointing to something which is beyond our psychology and beyond our physicality.

52
00:05:15,276 --> 00:05:18,279
And he reinforces

53
00:05:18,833 --> 00:05:24,918
what produced that, which was, of course, the destruction of all the defilements.

54
00:05:29,543 --> 00:05:32,127
My mind has attained the unconditioned.

55
00:05:32,766 --> 00:05:42,257
Unconditioned means that, or rather conditioned means that whatever that is relies on something else for its being there.

56
00:05:42,836 --> 00:05:44,718
A tree relies on oxygen.

57
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:47,322
So do we, yeah?

58
00:05:48,853 --> 00:05:50,855
We rely on food being gross.

59
00:05:51,216 --> 00:05:53,379
So that's what conditioned actually means.

60
00:05:54,319 --> 00:05:59,665
And our minds are conditioned by the society, the things we put into ourselves.

61
00:06:01,047 --> 00:06:08,314
So we're in constant interplay with our environment, which includes other people.

62
00:06:09,314 --> 00:06:12,738
But he says this is unconditioned, right?

63
00:06:12,759 --> 00:06:16,903
So it's something that doesn't need anything else.

64
00:06:17,795 --> 00:06:24,822
And he calls it the citta, which in a sense gives it a certain substance.

65
00:06:26,345 --> 00:06:27,607
Now, he doesn't like doing that.

66
00:06:28,548 --> 00:06:34,935
So it must have been a bit of a pain for him to say that, because that's one reason he doesn't like the self.

67
00:06:35,435 --> 00:06:44,427
So this self is the atman of the Hindu system, well, the Brahminical system, which referred to an eternal soul.

68
00:06:44,726 --> 00:06:48,853
And there was huge confusion at that time as to exactly what it was.

69
00:06:49,214 --> 00:06:53,281
And there were materialists that people said, you know, when you die, that's the end of it.

70
00:06:55,084 --> 00:07:07,505
So he stuck for words, but he clearly states that whatever he's experienced, once the house builder had been completely destroyed, was unconditioned.

71
00:07:09,249 --> 00:07:09,790
Okay.

72
00:07:10,732 --> 00:07:14,398
By the way, Freud, with his insights, had a similar problem.

73
00:07:14,437 --> 00:07:15,899
He had to make up words, didn't he?

74
00:07:16,420 --> 00:07:18,163
Id, ego, superego.

75
00:07:20,608 --> 00:07:22,449
Now, there's a very famous teacher.

76
00:07:22,470 --> 00:07:24,913
Some of you will know him, I think, Ajahn Mahabua.

77
00:07:25,235 --> 00:07:27,077
He died not so long ago.

78
00:07:27,117 --> 00:07:31,944
And he was understood to be an Arahant.

79
00:07:31,964 --> 00:07:34,949
He definitely said of himself that he no longer suffered.

80
00:07:35,841 --> 00:07:48,725
Now, in one meditation, and I think this might have been the point of his release from suffering, he's in meditation and he's in that place of just observing, et cetera, et cetera.

81
00:07:49,187 --> 00:07:53,213
And he says this Dharma, this teaching arose in him spontaneously.

82
00:07:53,814 --> 00:07:54,456
And this is it.

83
00:07:55,497 --> 00:07:59,706
If there is a point or a center of a knower meditation,

84
00:08:00,057 --> 00:08:25,052
anywhere that is the agent of birth the essence of continual becoming and that's exactly what the buddha discovered himself so it's something that we also will discover in time that whenever the self arises the world arises and we go into that world which is

85
00:08:25,858 --> 00:08:32,432
unless we are completely purified of defilements, is a cause of suffering for us, unsatisfactoriness.

86
00:08:33,996 --> 00:08:37,904
Now, this isn't something that is ethereal.

87
00:08:38,466 --> 00:08:42,014
Every time we wake up in the morning, that process happens.

88
00:08:42,514 --> 00:08:45,841
You wake up and you immediately recognize yourself.

89
00:08:47,138 --> 00:08:55,067
And many of you, I'm sure, have experienced waking up in a strange room in a hotel or somewhere and you don't know where you are.

90
00:08:55,147 --> 00:08:59,511
Just for that one moment, there's this little frisson, this little burst of fright.

91
00:08:59,652 --> 00:09:00,653
You don't know who you are.

92
00:09:01,975 --> 00:09:05,658
And then suddenly it's you and you feel safe again and happy.

93
00:09:06,519 --> 00:09:14,749
So that moment is telling us that there is a point as we wake up in the morning where we take on this sense of self.

94
00:09:16,871 --> 00:09:17,432
Okay.

95
00:09:18,634 --> 00:09:23,702
I just want to, you can go on about this forever, you know.

96
00:09:24,144 --> 00:09:30,514
So I just want to talk about, I just want to point out another way that he describes Nibbana.

97
00:09:32,157 --> 00:09:36,364
And this comes from the inspired sayings.

98
00:09:36,825 --> 00:09:41,192
There's a collection of his inspired sayings, the Udana Sutta.

99
00:09:43,770 --> 00:10:11,144
so it opens it just says that at one time the buddha was staying there savati and jetta's grove and artopindika's monastery and he was educating encouraging firing up and inspiring the mendicants with the dharma talk about now this is the word you see extinguishment okay but what we have to be clear about is what is actually extinguished and these mendicants were paying attention applying the mind concentrating wholeheartedly and actively listening

100
00:10:11,985 --> 00:10:17,793
Then, understanding this matter, on that occasion, the Buddha expressed this heartfelt sentiment.

101
00:10:18,855 --> 00:10:31,610
There is, O mendicants, that dimension where there is no earth, no water, no fire, no wind.

102
00:10:31,910 --> 00:10:34,514
So there's none of the four basic elements.

103
00:10:34,554 --> 00:10:36,697
That means there's nothing physical.

104
00:10:39,801 --> 00:10:41,823
No dimension of it.

105
00:10:42,158 --> 00:10:54,081
infinite space, no dimension of infinite consciousness, no dimension of nothingness, no dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.

106
00:10:54,101 --> 00:10:55,424
Those are the four

107
00:10:56,350 --> 00:11:14,793
what we call our rupa jhana, the four absorptions, the non-material absorptions, which is the most refined state that the mind can get into, where there's nothing in the mind of the body at all, not even images of the body, right?

108
00:11:15,975 --> 00:11:17,057
So there's not even that.

109
00:11:17,397 --> 00:11:23,184
So there's nothing from the physicality and there's nothing all the way through the mind.

110
00:11:25,004 --> 00:11:29,831
There is no this world, no other world, no moon, no sun.

111
00:11:34,659 --> 00:11:36,482
Yeah, so there's nothing there at all.

112
00:11:38,065 --> 00:11:46,259
There, mendicants, I say, there is no coming, no going, or remaining, or passing away, or reappearing.

113
00:11:46,599 --> 00:11:49,003
So there's no time and there's no space.

114
00:11:53,842 --> 00:11:55,686
Just this is the end of suffering.

115
00:11:56,868 --> 00:11:58,690
And he uses the word dimension.

116
00:11:58,910 --> 00:12:02,755
So this is another way that he describes consciousness.

117
00:12:03,998 --> 00:12:15,936
Ayatana, it comes up in the dependent origination and it's normally translated as the consciousnesses are based on the sense bases.

118
00:12:17,384 --> 00:12:22,291
So you have eye consciousness, ear consciousness, nose consciousness, etc.

119
00:12:22,451 --> 00:12:25,115
And you have heart-mind consciousness.

120
00:12:26,397 --> 00:12:26,677
Okay?

121
00:12:27,259 --> 00:12:34,308
And in the five khandhas, this consciousness is just a screen upon which information arises.

122
00:12:35,791 --> 00:12:40,899
And that screen is dependent upon those six sense spaces.

123
00:12:44,283 --> 00:12:46,868
He's saying that there is a dimension

124
00:12:47,707 --> 00:12:49,350
that is beyond all that.

125
00:12:51,293 --> 00:12:53,836
And he often refers to it as nibbana.

126
00:12:58,183 --> 00:12:59,566
And I'll leave you with a final one.

127
00:12:59,586 --> 00:13:00,748
We've just got a bit of time here.

128
00:13:02,110 --> 00:13:04,714
So again, the mendicants are paying attention.

129
00:13:04,974 --> 00:13:09,802
They're applying the mind, concentrating wholeheartedly and actively listening.

130
00:13:10,802 --> 00:13:16,010
And this is probably the most famous statement or the most well-known, shall we say.

131
00:13:16,884 --> 00:13:25,114
There is that which is never born, never lived, was never created or bound by conditions.

132
00:13:26,215 --> 00:13:41,510
If there was not that which was never born, never lived, was never created or bound by conditions, there would be no escape from that which is ever born, ever lived, ever created and bound by conditions.

133
00:13:42,251 --> 00:13:46,756
But since there is that which is never born, never lived,

134
00:13:47,142 --> 00:14:16,744
never created or bound by conditions there is an escape from that which is born ever lived ever created and bound by conditions and that's that's really his chosen way of expressing the transcendent by telling you what it's not and of course it's up to us now in our meditation practice to turn our attention towards those three characteristics

135
00:14:17,145 --> 00:14:29,225
Because that's where we will ourselves discover this dimension to see impermanence, to really see it and to see that there is a mechanism in us.

136
00:14:29,485 --> 00:14:39,340
This desire, which is born out of the self, is an expression of the self causing all these problems and that sense of not me, not mine.

137
00:14:43,522 --> 00:15:00,147
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, they have not caused confusion, and that by your diligent practice you will indeed break through the delusion and attain Nibbana sooner rather than later.

